result.execSummary:
The defendant Malik M Franks was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Misdemeanor Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Malik M Franks appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Thomas Paul Alberti appeared by video for Malik M Franks.  Attorney Ryan Jay Michaels appeared by video for State of Wisconsin. 

Case in court for Plea/ Sentencing Hearing.

Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defense and defendant are in agreement.

Pursuant to negotiations and on the Motion of the State, Court Ordered Count 1 and 3 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.

As to Count 2: Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Court vacates the previous plea and judgement of conviction entered on 08/22/2022.

Parties prepared to proceed with sentencing. State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law. Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.

As to Count 2: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 180 days  in the House of Correction, with credit for 180 days served. A TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.

Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.  

Conditions:
- Restitution set at zero.
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
- DV assessment imposed.
- All other court costs, fines, and surcharges are WAIVED due to inability to pay. 
- DNA surcharge and DV assessment are due by: 08/31/2023. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. 

*The defendant is advised of his/her appeal rights by defense counsel.
*Court advised defendant due to this DV conviction he may never possess firearms or ammunition.
